"""
mkt-context: Hosea ch7-12 — historical/ANE background commentary.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hosea-7-12.py

Historical context:
  - Setting: Northern Kingdom (Israel/Ephraim), c. 750-722 BCE, final decades before
    Assyrian conquest and deportation under Tiglath-Pileser III (745-727) and
    Shalmaneser V / Sargon II (722 fall of Samaria).
  - Political chaos: Israel had 6 kings in its last 25 years, most assassinated;
    the royal succession instability is background to ch7's 'heated oven' imagery.
  - Foreign policy: Israel vacillated between paying tribute to Assyria and seeking
    Egyptian alliance — Hosea's 'silly dove' (7:11) and 'hiring Assyrian lovers' (8:9).
  - Key ANE backgrounds: Baal-Peor incident (9:10), calf worship at Bethel/Dan
    (8:5-6), Jacob-traditions used as mirror (ch12), father-son covenant language (ch11).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The opening of ch7 places the prophecy in the context of the final decades of the Northern Kingdom (Israel/Ephraim), whose capital was Samaria. 'When I would have healed Israel, the iniquity of Ephraim was revealed, and the evil deeds of Samaria.' The phrase 'troop of robbers' (<em>gedud</em>) raiding outside while thieves break in reflects the political anarchy of the period: between 752 and 722 BCE, Israel had six kings, most removed through assassination. Zechariah (752), Shallum (752), Pekahiah (740), and Pekah (732) were all killed by successors. The simultaneous external raiding and internal theft mirrors this political violence at every level of society.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'They do not consider that I remember all their evil' — the failure to reckon with divine memory. The phrase 'their deeds surround them' uses the verb <em>sabab</em> (to surround/encircle), echoing military siege language. The theological claim is that Israel's sins have become their own besiegers — a restatement of the Deuteronomic principle that covenant violations bring their own consequences (Deut 28:15-68). The contrast with v1 ('when I would have healed') establishes the pattern: divine initiative toward restoration met with human obliviousness.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'They make the king glad with their evil, and the princes with their lies.' The court culture of the Northern Kingdom's final years was one of mutual flattery and conspiracy. The word-pair king/princes (<em>melek/sarim</em>) recurs in Hosea's oracles as the locus of political corruption: these are the very officials who should enforce covenant justice (cf. Deut 17:14-20 on the king's role) but who instead reward the culture of deception. The 'lies' (<em>kazab</em>) that delight the court are both political (false alliances) and religious (false prophecy).</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They are all adulterers; they are like a heated oven whose baker ceases to stir the fire' — an extended metaphor from bread-baking. The image: a baker heats the oven intensely, then does nothing while the dough rises and ferments overnight, so that by morning the fire blazes without further attention. The 'adulterers' are likely the court conspirators (picking up the covenant unfaithfulness theme); the baker who stops stirring represents the conspirators who set the plot in motion and then wait for it to ignite. Ancient bread ovens (<em>tannur</em>) were clay domes heated from outside — an apt image for smoldering conspiracy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'On the day of our king, the princes became sick with the heat of wine; he stretched out his hand with mockers.' Royal feast days were occasions of political alliance and loyalty demonstration in the ANE — comparable to the Assyrian marzea banquet or Egyptian royal celebration. The 'heat of wine' (<em>chamat yayin</em>) is not merely drunkenness but the feverish intensity of the conspiratorial atmosphere. The stretching out of hands 'with mockers' (<em>lotzetzim</em>) — a term from Proverbs for those who scorn wisdom — indicates the king fraternizing with those who mock covenant values.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Their heart is like an oven; they approach with intrigue; their anger smolders all night; in the morning it blazes like a flaming fire.' The oven metaphor continues and intensifies: the night is the time of hidden conspiracy, the morning the time of violent action. This pattern fits the historical pattern of palace coups in Israel: Shallum's assassination of Zechariah (2 Kings 15:10), Menahem's brutal suppression of Tiphsah (2 Kings 15:16), and Pekah's assassination of Pekahiah (2 Kings 15:25) all had this pattern of plot and sudden violent execution.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'All of them are hot as an oven, and they devour their rulers. All their kings have fallen, and none of them calls to me.' The summary statement of Israel's political crisis: 'all their kings have fallen' — a historical observation about the rapid succession of murdered monarchs. The count: between Jeroboam II's long stable reign (793-753) and the fall of Samaria (722), Israel had five kings murdered. The culminating indictment is not political but theological: 'none of them calls to me' — the fundamental absence of <em>teshuvah</em> (turning/repentance) even in crisis.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Ephraim mixes himself with the peoples; Ephraim is a cake not turned.' The 'flat cake not turned' (<em>ugah beli hafucha</em>) is a precise cooking image: bread cooked on only one side is burned on the bottom and raw on top — ruined. The mixing (<em>yitbolal</em>) with foreign peoples refers to Israel's practice of political and religious syncretism: seeking foreign alliances (Assyria, Egypt) while adopting their religious practices. The half-baked image captures the political condition: Israel was partially Assyrianized (paying tribute, adopting Assyrian cult practices) while remaining partially Israelite — satisfying no one and fulfilling no purpose.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Strangers devour his strength, and he knows it not; gray hairs are sprinkled upon him, and he knows it not.' The 'strangers' are the foreign powers drawing Israel's economic and political resources — specifically Assyria, to whom Israel was paying tribute from the time of Menahem (2 Kings 15:19-20: Menahem paid 1000 talents of silver to Tiglath-Pileser III). The 'gray hairs' image is of a man aging without realizing it — the gradual diminishment of national vitality that accompanies the drain of tribute. The double 'knows it not' (<em>velo yada</em>) is the book's repeated diagnosis: Israel's fundamental condition is willful ignorance of its spiritual state.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'The pride of Israel testifies to his face; yet they do not return to the LORD their God, nor seek him, for all this.' The 'pride of Israel' (<em>ge'on Yisrael</em>) as a divine title appears also in Amos 8:7 ('sworn by the pride of Jacob') — there referring to God himself. Here the meaning is ambiguous: it may mean Israel's pride testifies against Israel, or that YHWH (as Israel's true pride) testifies against their face. The phrase 'for all this' (<em>bekhol-zot</em>) appears in Isaiah as a refrain after a series of judgments — suggesting that even in the midst of the judgments already falling, Israel has not turned.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Ephraim is like a dove, silly and without sense, calling to Egypt, going to Assyria.' The 'silly dove' (<em>yonah potah ein lev</em>) captures Israel's foreign policy precisely. Between 727 and 722 BCE, king Hoshea of Israel pursued exactly this strategy: 2 Kings 17:3-4 records that Hoshea first submitted to Shalmaneser V (Assyrian), then secretly sent messengers to So king of Egypt seeking an alliance against Assyria. The dove without heart (<em>ein lev</em>) is a creature that flutters between perches without fixed purpose — the exact political behavior. Egypt could not and did not help; Assyria invaded and destroyed Samaria in 722.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'As they go, I will spread my net over them; I will bring them down like birds of the heavens.' The divine net over the dove — the metaphor shifts from the dove as Israel's self-image to YHWH as the fowler who catches it. Bird-catching with nets was common in both Egypt and Canaan; ANE art depicts large spread nets capturing birds in flight. The chastisement 'according to the report to their congregation' may refer to the divine assembly's decision or to a proclamation — the exact phrase is disputed, but the point is clear: Israel's flight between the great powers will be cut short by divine intervention.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Woe to them, for they have strayed from me! Destruction to them, for they have rebelled against me! I would redeem them, but they speak lies against me.' The double woe (<em>oy/shadod</em>) is the form of prophetic lament over impending destruction — used for the dying and the dead (cf. 1 Kings 13:30). The crucial verb 'redeem' (<em>padah</em>) is covenant-ransom language: YHWH speaks as a kinsman-redeemer who has the right and desire to ransom Israel from captivity, but Israel's lies prevent the transaction. The lies here are both cultic (false worship) and political (false alliances treating Assyria as savior).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'They do not cry to me from the heart, but they wail upon their beds; for grain and wine they gash themselves; they rebel against me.' The 'wailing upon beds' and 'gashing' (<em>yitgorereu</em>) refer to mourning rituals — possibly the ritual lacerations associated with Canaanite Baal worship during drought (cf. 1 Kings 18:28, Baal's prophets cutting themselves). The contrast is with genuine prayer (<em>tza'aq min-halev</em>, crying from the heart): Israel's ritual mourning is aimed at securing agricultural fertility from Baal, not at genuine covenant return to YHWH. The grain and wine they seek are the Baal-cult's domain.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Although I trained and strengthened their arms, yet they devise evil against me.' The 'training' (<em>yissarti</em>) and 'strengthening' (<em>chizzaqti</em>) of arms invokes the patron-deity relationship of ANE warfare: a deity trains and strengthens his people for battle (cf. Ps 144:1: 'who trains my hands for war'). The irony is that the military strength Israel used to seek foreign alliances (relying on horses and chariots: Isa 31:1) was a strength YHWH himself had given — used now in rebellion against its source.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'They return, but not upward; they are like a treacherous bow; their princes shall fall by the sword because of the rage of their tongue. This shall be their derision in the land of Egypt.' The 'treacherous bow' (<em>qeshet remiyah</em>, also in Ps 78:57) is one that looks functional but misfires — the string is loose, the shot goes wide. Israel's 'returns' (<em>yeshuvu</em>) are the same problem as its foreign policy: superficial, misdirected. 'Because of the rage of their tongue' — the anti-Assyrian conspiracy that led to the Egyptian alliance (2 Kings 17:4) became the occasion for Egypt to mock Israel when that alliance failed to save Samaria.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>'Set the trumpet to your lips! One like a vulture is over the house of the LORD.' The trumpet (<em>shofar</em>) is the alarm signal for enemy attack (cf. Amos 3:6, Joel 2:1); the 'vulture' or eagle (<em>nesher</em>) over 'the house of the LORD' is Assyria — the eagle/vulture image for Assyrian military power appears in Deut 28:49 as a covenant curse. 'The house of the LORD' in this context likely refers to the land of Israel as YHWH's household (cf. Num 12:7), not merely the temple — all of Israel is about to be invaded. The verse is a vivid alarm cry.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'To me they cry, My God, we — Israel — know you.' The cry 'My God' (<em>eli</em>) acknowledges the covenant relationship while the behavior of chs7-8 contradicts it. The phrase 'we know you' (<em>yeda'nucha</em>) uses the covenant-knowledge term (<em>yada</em>) that Hosea has been developing throughout the book (2:20, 4:1, 6:3, 6:6); 'knowing God' is the core of the covenant relationship. The problem is that Israel claims <em>yada</em> while practicing the opposite — this is the covenant breach in its most precise form.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Israel has spurned the good; the enemy shall pursue him.' The 'good' (<em>tov</em>) that Israel has rejected is the covenant blessing — the total package of YHWH's gifts including law, land, and relationship (cf. Mic 6:8: 'he has told you, O man, what is good'). The connection to Deuteronomy is direct: Deut 30:15 sets before Israel 'life and good' vs 'death and evil'; rejection of the good activates the death-curse. The 'enemy' who will pursue is the Assyrian army — the human instrument of the covenant curse of Deut 28:25.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They made kings, but not through me. They set up princes, but I knew it not. With their silver and gold they made idols for their own destruction.' The indictment has two parallel elements: illegitimate monarchy and illegitimate cult. On monarchy: the Northern Kingdom's very founding was a covenant breach (1 Kings 12); its succession by assassination further violated Deut 17's requirements for kingship. On idols: the word 'destruction' (<em>lema'an yikaret</em>, so that they may be cut off) makes the idol-making itself self-destructive — the cult objects designed for protection actually accelerate judgment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'I have spurned your calf, O Samaria. My anger burns against them. How long will they be incapable of innocence?' 'Your calf' (<em>egelech Shomron</em>) refers to the golden calves established by Jeroboam I at Bethel and Dan (1 Kings 12:26-33) as a substitute for Jerusalem temple worship. The calves were bull/calf pedestals — a form common in Canaanite iconography where the deity stands on or is represented by a bull. The phrase 'calf of Samaria' links the ancient apostasy to the current Samaritan religious establishment. 'How long will they be incapable of innocence?' (<em>ad matay yuchal le-niqayon</em>) — the question of moral capacity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'For it is from Israel! A craftsman made it; it is not God. The calf of Samaria shall be broken to pieces.' The demystification of the idol: 'a craftsman made it' (<em>charash asahu</em>) — the same argument developed at length in Isa 44:9-20 and Hab 2:18-19. The making of the calf by a craftsman is a direct parallel to the golden calf of Exodus 32:4 ('Aaron fashioned it with a graving tool'). The prediction that the calf 'shall be broken to pieces' is historically fulfilled when the Assyrians carried off temple equipment as plunder — the captured deity was the standard ancient demonstration of victory.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'For they sow the wind, and they shall reap the whirlwind. The standing grain has no heads; it shall yield no flour; if it were to yield, strangers would devour it.' The proverb 'sow wind, reap whirlwind' captures the agricultural metaphor perfectly: wind sowing (futile action) produces whirlwind (catastrophic, disproportionate consequences). The harvest imagery develops the point: even if grain grows (<em>qamah</em>), it will have no head (<em>tzemach bal ya'aseh qemach</em>) — the stalk without grain is a common crop failure. And even if grain did develop, 'strangers would devour it' — the tribute economy of Assyrian domination left Israel with ever-diminishing harvests to enjoy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Israel is swallowed up; already they are among the nations as a useless vessel.' The 'swallowing up' (<em>nivla</em>) of Israel anticipates the actual deportation: 2 Kings 17:6 records that the king of Assyria 'carried the Israelites away to Assyria and placed them in Halah, and on the Habor, the river of Gozan, and in the cities of the Medes.' The 'useless vessel' (<em>keli ein chefetz bo</em>) echoes Jer 22:28 (applied to Coniah) — a broken pot, thrown away. The deportation of the northern tribes dispersed them so thoroughly that they became historically unidentifiable as a distinct entity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'For they have gone up to Assyria, a wild donkey wandering alone; Ephraim has hired lovers.' The 'wild donkey wandering alone' (<em>pere bod'ed</em>) is a solitary, uncontrollable animal — the image of Israel's unilateral foreign policy decisions made without YHWH. Menahem's tribute to Tiglath-Pileser III (745-727 BCE) is recorded in the Assyrian annals: 'Menahem of Samaria... to preserve his lordship I imposed [tribute] upon him.' Israel 'hiring lovers' uses the marriage metaphor: a wife who pays her own lovers is not merely unfaithful but has inverted the relationship entirely — grace replaced by payment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Though they hire allies among the nations, I will soon gather them up. And the king and princes shall writhe because of the tribute.' The gathering (<em>ve'aqabtzem</em>) is ironic: YHWH will 'gather' Israel — but in judgment, not blessing (contrast the eschatological gathering of Isa 11:12). The burden of tribute (<em>massa</em>) to the 'great king' — a title for the Assyrian monarch also in 5:13 and in the Assyrian royal inscriptions themselves — had become crushing: 2 Kings 15:19-20 records Menahem taxing all wealthy Israelites 50 shekels each to raise 1000 talents of silver for Pul (Tiglath-Pileser).</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Because Ephraim has multiplied altars for sinning, they have become for him altars for sinning.' The theological pun: altars designed for worship (<em>chet</em>, sin-offering altars) become the mechanism of sin. The multiplied altars violated Deuteronomy 12's requirement for centralized worship at one place — a requirement that the Deuteronomists interpreted as demanding worship only at Jerusalem. The Northern Kingdom's many high places and local sanctuaries, even if sincere, were formally in breach. But Hosea's point is deeper: the altars have become the occasion for Baal-syncretism, so even the form of the worship has become corrupt.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Were I to write for him my law by ten thousands, they would be regarded as a strange thing.' The 'ten thousands' (<em>ribbo</em>) of written law (<em>torot</em>) suggests the fullness of divine instruction — the written Torah as a gracious gift. 'Regarded as a strange thing' (<em>kezar nechshabu</em>) — the word <em>zar</em> means foreign/strange/alien. Israel treats its own covenant law as if it were the law of another nation — unrecognizable, alien, irrelevant. This is one of the most damning indictments in the prophets: not that Israel lacks the law, but that it treats its own covenant instruction as foreign.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'As for my sacrificial offerings, they sacrifice meat and eat it, but the LORD does not accept them. Now he will remember their iniquity and punish their sins; they shall return to Egypt.' The critique here is not of the sacrificial system itself but of its use: 'they sacrifice meat and eat it' — the sacrifices have become merely ceremonial meals, detached from covenant relationship. The punishment 'they shall return to Egypt' is a deliberate reversal of the Exodus: the foundational act of salvation is undone. Some Israelites did flee to Egypt after the Assyrian conquest (cf. 2 Kings 25:26 for later Judean parallels).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'For Israel has forgotten his Maker and built palaces, and Judah has multiplied fortified cities; so I will send a fire upon his cities, and it shall devour his strongholds.' The charge against Israel is 'forgetting its Maker' (<em>shakhach Yisrael et-osav</em>) — the verb <em>shakach</em> for forgetting is prominent in Deuteronomy as a covenant-curse trigger (Deut 8:11-14). 'Building palaces' (<em>heikhalot</em>) as the expression of forgetting recalls the Deuteronomic warning against prosperity-induced amnesia (Deut 8:12-14: 'when you have built fine houses'). Judah's multiplied fortified cities reflects the real historical military buildup under Uzziah and Jotham.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>'Rejoice not, O Israel! Exult not like the peoples; for you have played the whore, forsaking your God. You have loved a prostitute's wages on all threshing floors.' The autumn harvest festival (Sukkoth/Tabernacles) was the occasion of great joy in the agricultural cycle — grain, wine, and oil had been gathered. The threshing floor was the site of celebration and also of fertility cult practices: the Canaanite harvest festivals at the threshing floor involved ritual enactment of Baal's fertility, including sexual rites. Hosea condemns Israel's harvest celebration as cult prostitution — the 'wages' (<em>etnan</em>, the technical term for a harlot's fee) are the grain harvests Israel thinks she receives from Baal.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Threshing floor and wine vat shall not feed them, and the new wine shall fail them.' The threat is agricultural deprivation — not through drought alone but through the Assyrian conquest that would redirect harvests to tribute. The 'threshing floor' (<em>goren</em>) and 'wine vat' (<em>yekev</em>) represent the two main harvest seasons (grain in spring/early summer, grapes in late summer/fall). The failure of the new wine (<em>tirosh</em>) is specifically the Baal-cult's domain: if Baal cannot deliver the harvest he was supposedly producing, the entire religious-agricultural system collapses.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'They shall not remain in the LORD's land, but Ephraim shall return to Egypt, and they shall eat unclean food in Assyria.' The covenant land is 'the LORD's land' (<em>admat YHWH</em>) — Israel as tenant in YHWH's estate (cf. Lev 25:23). Expulsion from the land reverses the land-grant. 'Return to Egypt' activates the Deuteronomic curse formula (Deut 28:68: 'The LORD will bring you back in ships to Egypt'). 'Unclean food in Assyria' refers to the inability to maintain Levitical food purity laws in exile — the Assyrian captivity would make kosher observance practically impossible, symbolizing full covenant rupture.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They shall not pour drink offerings of wine to the LORD, and their sacrifices shall not please him. It shall be like mourners' bread to them; all who eat of it shall be defiled; for their bread shall be for their hunger only; it shall not come to the house of the LORD.' Mourners' bread (<em>lechem onim</em>) was bread in a house of death — Num 19:14 makes a corpse in a tent ceremonially unclean everything in it. Sacrifices and offerings require ritual purity; in exile, with constant contact with the dead of battle and the impurities of foreign soil, the sacrificial system would be impossible. All food becomes 'mourning bread' — merely sustaining the body with no covenantal dimension.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'What will you do on the day of the appointed festival, and on the day of the feast of the LORD?' The 'appointed feast' (<em>mo'ed</em>) and 'feast of YHWH' (<em>chag YHWH</em>) are the three pilgrimage festivals: Passover/Unleavened Bread, Weeks (Shavuot/Pentecost), and Tabernacles (Sukkoth). These required pilgrimage to the sanctuary and communal celebration — impossible in exile. The question has a biting irony: Israel celebrates the harvest feasts now; what will she do in Assyria, far from land and sanctuary? The answer implied is: she will have no feasts to celebrate.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'For behold, they are going away from destruction; but Egypt shall gather them; Memphis shall bury them. Nettles shall possess their precious things of silver; thorns shall be in their tents.' Memphis (<em>Mof</em>) was a major Egyptian city and burial center in the Nile Delta, famous for its royal necropolises. The irony: Israel flees to Egypt for safety and finds only burial there — Egypt becomes a graveyard. The silver 'precious things' (<em>machmad kaspa</em>) now overgrown with nettles and thorns recalls the Deuteronomic vision of the land cursed — the agricultural fruitfulness reverting to wilderness (Isa 5:6).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The days of punishment have come; the days of recompense have come; Israel shall know it. The prophet is a fool; the man of the spirit is mad, because of your great iniquity and great hatred.' The 'days of punishment' (<em>yemei hapequddah</em>) are the prophetically announced day of YHWH's visitation — now arrived. The stunning claim that 'the prophet is a fool' (<em>nabhi evel</em>) and 'the man of the spirit is mad' (<em>meshugga</em>) reflects how the true prophet appears to a society that has rejected prophetic warning: when judgment comes and the prophet is proved right, the people's response is to dismiss him as mad. This is the social reception of authentic prophecy.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The prophet is the watchman of Ephraim with my God; yet a fowler's snare is on all his ways, and hatred in the house of his God.' The watchman (<em>tzofeh</em>) metaphor appears in Ezekiel 3:17 and 33:7 as the normative description of the prophet's social role: stationed on the wall to see approaching enemies and warn the city. Hosea's prophetic role as Israel's watchman is validated by YHWH ('with my God') even as the prophet is persecuted. The 'fowler's snare' on his ways and 'hatred in the house of his God' suggest that the prophet himself is hunted — the recipients of the warning have become the danger.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'They have deeply corrupted themselves as in the days of Gibeah: he will remember their iniquity; he will punish their sins.' The days of Gibeah (<em>kimei hagiv'ah</em>) refer to the outrage of Judges 19-20: the gang rape and murder of the Levite's concubine by Benjaminites of Gibeah, followed by a near-annihilation of the tribe of Benjamin in civil war. It is among the most shameful episodes in the book of Judges, the culmination of the 'everyone did what was right in his own eyes' cycle. Hosea uses it as the benchmark of Israel's moral degradation: the present sin is as deep as the worst moment in the tribal period.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Like grapes in the wilderness, I found Israel. Like the first fruit on the fig tree in its first season, I saw your fathers. But they came to Baal-peor and consecrated themselves to the thing of shame, and became detestable like the thing they loved.' The wilderness discovery — 'like grapes in the wilderness' — captures the unexpected delight of the Exodus encounter: finding fruit in an impossible place. The first-fruit fig is the first ripe fruit of the season, eaten with special pleasure. The tender image of the honeymoon period (cf. Jer 2:2: 'the devotion of your youth, your love as a bride') contrasts with the immediate apostasy at Baal-Peor (Num 25:1-9): Israel arrived at the threshold of Canaan and immediately worshipped the Moabite fertility deity, with the deaths of 24,000 as consequence.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Ephraim's glory shall fly away like a bird — no birth, no pregnancy, no conception!' The threefold curse on fertility — birth, pregnancy, conception — moves backward through the reproductive sequence, as if undoing creation itself. The word for glory (<em>kavod</em>) can also mean 'weight/wealth' — Ephraim's honor and offspring will literally fly away. In ANE thought, the deity's departure (the <em>melammu</em> leaving) signaled the city's fall; here YHWH's withdrawal from Ephraim is expressed as reproductive failure, the anti-blessing of Deut 28:18 ('cursed shall be the fruit of your womb').</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Even if they bring up children, I will bereave them till none is left. Woe to them when I depart from them!' The bereavement (<em>shikkalti</em>) language is from the root used for a mother bereaved of her child — one of the most intense grief images in the Hebrew Bible (cf. Jer 31:15, Rachel weeping for her children). The climax 'woe to them when I depart from them' (<em>gam-oy lahem besuri meihem</em>) — the 'departure' of YHWH from Ephraim is the theological reality that all the military, agricultural, and political disasters express. The <em>kabod</em> (glory/presence) of YHWH departing is the ultimate catastrophe.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Ephraim, as I have seen, was like Tyre, planted in a meadow; but Ephraim must lead his children out to slaughter.' The comparison to Tyre is surprising — Tyre was famous for its island stronghold, its maritime wealth, and its security. The image of being 'planted in a meadow' (<em>nata benave</em>) suggests settled, flourishing life. The reversal is abrupt: this flourishing Ephraim 'must lead his children out to slaughter' — the very acts of parenting (bringing children into the world, raising them) end in military conscription and death. The soldier-children image anticipates the Assyrian conquest's mass casualties.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Give them, O LORD — what will you give? Give them a miscarrying womb and dry breasts.' The prophet intercedes but struggles with what to ask for. The 'miscarrying womb' (<em>rechem mashkil</em>) and 'dry breasts' (<em>shadayim tzimchonim</em>) are not a curse but a mercy — better that children not be born than that they be born into the fate of Assyrian conquest. The prayer echoes the terrible calculus of Lamentations 4:9 (better to die by sword than famine) and anticipates Jesus' words in Luke 23:29: 'Blessed are the barren and the wombs that never bore.' In extreme judgment, childlessness is protective.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Every evil of theirs is in Gilgal; there I began to hate them. Because of the wickedness of their deeds I will drive them out of my house. I will love them no more; all their princes are rebels.' Gilgal was Israel's first camp after crossing the Jordan (Josh 4-5), where the covenant was renewed, the men circumcised, and the Passover kept. By Hosea's time it had become a center of corrupt worship (cf. 4:15, 12:11, Amos 4:4, 5:5). The irony of covenant renewal becoming the seat of covenant violation makes it the symbolic starting point of divine 'hatred' — the covenantal use of <em>sane</em> (hate) means the withdrawal of covenant love, not personal animosity (cf. Mal 1:2-3).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Ephraim is stricken; their root is dried up; they shall bear no fruit. Even though they give birth, I will put their beloved children to death.' The botanical metaphor — dried root, no fruit — is the death of the vine. The vine as Israel metaphor appears in Ps 80:8-16, Isa 5:1-7, and extensively in Ezekiel 15-17. A vine with a dried root is not merely unproductive but irreversibly dead. The 'beloved children' (<em>machmad bitnam</em>) — the most precious offspring — will be killed. This points to the historical reality: the Assyrian conquest involved mass slaughter, and the Assyrian policy of deportation broke family units permanently.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'My God will reject them because they have not listened to him; they shall be wanderers among the nations.' The divine rejection (<em>yim'asem</em>) uses the same verb as God rejecting Saul's kingship (1 Sam 15:23, 26; 16:1). 'Wanderers among the nations' (<em>yihyu nodedim bagoyim</em>) — the noun <em>nad</em> is used in Gen 4:12 of Cain's curse after murdering Abel: 'a fugitive and a wanderer on the earth.' The connection is pointed: fratricide resulted in exile and wandering; Israel's spiritual adultery (killing the covenant relationship) results in the same. The Diaspora of the northern tribes — scattered so thoroughly they became 'the lost ten tribes' — is the historical fulfillment.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>'Israel is a luxuriant vine that yields its fruit. The more his fruit increased, the more altars he built; as his country improved, he improved his pillars.' The vine is a standard OT symbol for Israel (Ps 80:8-16, Isa 5:1-7). The irony is exact: the more the vine flourished (prosperity under Jeroboam II, c. 793-753, Israel's last period of expansion and wealth), the more Israel multiplied altars (<em>mizbechot</em>) and sacred pillars (<em>matsevot</em>). The pillars (<em>matsevot</em>) were standing stones — both legitimate memorial markers and Canaanite fertility cult objects. Prosperity funded idolatry rather than gratitude.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Their heart is false; now they must bear their guilt. The LORD will break down their altars and destroy their pillars.' The 'divided heart' (<em>chalaq</em>) — the root means smooth/slippery/divided; a divided loyalty between YHWH and Baal. The punishment fits the sin: the altars multiplied in prosperity will be broken down in judgment. Archaeological evidence from the Northern Kingdom sites (Megiddo, Hazor, Dan) shows both YHWH-worship and Baal worship artifacts in the same strata — the material culture confirms Hosea's diagnosis of syncretism.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'For now they will say: We have no king, for we do not fear the LORD; and a king — what could he do for us?' The anticipated situation of post-conquest statelessness: without king or covenant, the two institutions that defined Israelite political identity collapse together. The connection between 'no king' and 'we do not fear the LORD' is the Deuteronomic logic: the king exists to enforce covenant justice (Deut 17:18-20); if covenant is broken, kingship is purposeless. The rhetorical question 'what could he do for us?' captures the helplessness of a people whose institutional structures have proved hollow.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They utter mere words; with empty oaths they make covenants; so judgment springs up like poisonous weeds in the furrows of the field.' The 'empty oaths' and 'covenants' likely refer to international treaties — the political alliances with Assyria and Egypt — made with ritual oath-formulas but without substance or fidelity. The hemlock/poisonous weeds (<em>rosh</em>) that spring up in the furrows is a brilliant agricultural-legal image: the covenant lawsuit (<em>mishpat</em>) that should produce justice has instead produced poison. Rosh appears in the covenant curse vocabulary (Deut 29:18) as the plant of bitterness.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The inhabitants of Samaria tremble for the calf of Beth-aven. Its people mourn for it, and so do its idolatrous priests — those who rejoiced over it and over its glory — for it has departed from them.' 'Beth-aven' ('house of wickedness') is Hosea's contemptuous pun on 'Beth-el' ('house of God'). The 'calf' taken into exile was not metaphorical: when Assyria conquered a city, they carried off the cult statue as the ultimate sign of divine abandonment and military victory — the god had been 'captured.' The 'glory' (<em>kavod</em>) departing from the calf is the obverse of YHWH's presence/glory departing from Israel.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The thing itself shall be carried to Assyria as tribute to the great king. Ephraim shall be put to shame, and Israel shall be ashamed of his idol.' 'The great king' (<em>melek yarev</em>) is likely 'Jareb' as a title meaning 'contender/warrior' for the Assyrian monarch — or a title meaning 'great king' in Akkadian (<em>sharru rabbu</em>). Assyrian royal inscriptions from Tiglath-Pileser III and Sargon II list the gods and cult objects taken from conquered cities among their booty. The 'shame' (<em>bosh/chapher</em>) of Israel at her idol being carried off is the shame of the patron whose deity has been captured — the ultimate religious humiliation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Samaria's king shall perish like a twig on the face of the waters.' The king as a floating piece of wood on water — ephemeral, helpless, carried wherever the current goes. Samaria's last king was Hoshea, who was arrested by Shalmaneser V (2 Kings 17:4) and imprisoned; the city was then besieged for three years before falling in 722 to Sargon II. The 'foam on the face of the waters' (<em>qetzef al-penei mayim</em>) is an image of absolute impermanence — completely at the mercy of forces beyond control.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The high places of Aven, the sin of Israel, shall be destroyed. Thorn and thistle shall grow up on their altars, and they shall say to the mountains, Cover us, and to the hills, Fall on us.' 'Aven' (wickedness) = Beth-aven = Beth-el. Thorn and thistle growing over deserted altars is the reversal of cultivation — the agricultural imagery of the covenant blessing reversed (Gen 3:18: thorns and thistles as the curse). 'Cover us... fall on us' — the cry to be buried under mountains is the ultimate expression of shame-flight: better to be crushed than to face the coming judgment. Jesus quotes this exact phrase in Luke 23:30 (to the daughters of Jerusalem) and it appears in Rev 6:16 (the sixth seal).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'From the days of Gibeah, you have sinned, O Israel; there they have continued. Shall not the war against the unjust overtake them in Gibeah?' The second Gibeah reference in Hosea (cf. 9:9) — the outrage of Judges 19-20 as the originary sin. The phrase 'there they have continued' (<em>sham amadu</em>) suggests an unbroken line of moral continuity from the Benjaminite atrocity to the present. The 'war against the unjust' (<em>milchamah al-benei aven</em>) at Gibeah resulted in near-annihilation of Benjamin; the coming Assyrian war against Israel will be the same scale of judgment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'When I please, I will discipline them, and nations shall be gathered against them when they are bound up for their double iniquity.' The 'double iniquity' (<em>she'tey avonot</em>) is debated: it may refer to the double sin of Bethel and Dan (the two calf-worship sites), or to the twin sins of political and religious apostasy, or to the twofold calf (the two golden calves). The gathering of nations against Israel is the Assyrian coalition that Tiglath-Pileser III assembled — his inscriptions record bringing various vassal armies against the Levant. Divine sovereignty is expressed through Assyrian military power.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Ephraim was a trained calf that loved to thresh, and I spared her fair neck; but I will put Ephraim to the yoke; Judah must plow; Jacob must harrow for himself.' The threshing-calf was a privileged animal: in the ANE, oxen were not muzzled while threshing (Deut 25:4 — 'do not muzzle an ox when it treads out grain'), so the animal ate while it worked. Ephraim 'loved to thresh' because threshing was light work with abundant reward. The shift to plowing is punitive — harder, less pleasant labor. The agricultural progression (threshing → plowing → harrowing) represents the reversal of privilege into labor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Sow for yourselves righteousness; reap steadfast love; break up your fallow ground, for it is the time to seek the LORD, that he may come and rain righteousness upon you.' The most positive appeal in ch10 — an invitation to covenantal restoration using agricultural metaphor. 'Fallow ground' (<em>nir</em>) is unplowed land that needs to be broken up before it can receive seed — the hardened heart of Israel needs breaking before the rain of righteousness can take effect. The 'rain of righteousness' (<em>moreh tzedeq</em>) anticipates the 'Teacher of Righteousness' concept in later Jewish thought and the NT figure of the one who brings the Spirit like rain.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'You have plowed iniquity; you have reaped injustice; you have eaten the fruit of lies. Because you have trusted in your own way and in the multitude of your warriors.' The inversion of v12: instead of sowing righteousness, Israel has plowed iniquity. The 'multitude of warriors' (<em>rob giborim</em>) is the military trust that Deuteronomy (17:16) and the prophets consistently condemn — horse, chariot, and numbers as false security. Israel's military buildup under Jeroboam II included significant chariot forces, but these proved useless against the Assyrian military machine.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Therefore the tumult of war shall arise among your people, and all your fortresses shall be destroyed, as Shalman destroyed Beth-arbel on the day of battle; mothers were dashed in pieces with their children.' 'Shalman' is likely Shalmaneser V of Assyria (727-722 BCE) who besieged Samaria; 'Beth-arbel' may be Arbela in Galilee (modern Irbid or Arbela). The destruction of Beth-arbel by Shalman was evidently proverbial for extreme brutality — 'mothers dashed in pieces with their children' is the horror formula for complete massacre (cf. 2 Kings 8:12, Isa 13:16, Ps 137:9). The historical atrocity becomes the image of what is coming to all of Israel's fortresses.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Thus it shall be done to you, O Bethel, because of your great evil. At dawn the king of Israel shall be utterly cut off.' The prophecy against Bethel is a reversal: Bethel was the site of Jacob's dream (Gen 28), the original house of God — but under Jeroboam I became the primary calf-worship center (1 Kings 12:29). The 'king of Israel utterly cut off at dawn' (<em>nidmoh nidmah melek Yisrael</em>, cut off utterly = a strong double form) points to the actual end: Hoshea, the last king of Israel, was imprisoned; Samaria fell; the monarchy ended abruptly, like the extinguishing of a light at dawn.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>'When Israel was a child, I loved him, and out of Egypt I called my son.' The father-son metaphor for the covenant relationship represents one of the most intimate images of divine-human relationship in the OT. 'Called my son' (<em>mMitzraim qara'ti livni</em>) refers to the Exodus as the moment of divine calling — YHWH naming Israel as son and calling him out of Egypt. This verse becomes one of the NT's key OT citations: Matthew 2:15 applies it to the return of the infant Jesus from Egypt ('out of Egypt I called my son'), making the Exodus pattern the template for Christ's history. Hosea's use establishes the father-son relationship as foundational to understanding the covenant.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'The more they were called, the more they went away; they kept sacrificing to the Baals and burning offerings to idols.' The more YHWH called (<em>kara</em>) — the very verb of the Exodus call — the more Israel fled toward Baal. The Baal worship in the Northern Kingdom was most intense during the Omride dynasty (9th century): Ahab's marriage to Jezebel of Sidon brought systematic Baal worship (1 Kings 16:31-33), including a Baal temple in Samaria. Though Jehu destroyed the Baal temple (2 Kings 10:27-28), the altars and high places remained throughout the 8th century.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Yet it was I who taught Ephraim to walk; I took them up by their arms, but they did not know that I healed them.' The image of YHWH teaching Israel to walk (<em>tirgalti le-Ephraim qacha'tam al-zero'otam</em>) — walking with a toddler, holding by the arms — is one of the most tender parenting images in Scripture. The word <em>rapha</em> (healed) suggests that the walking-teaching was also a healing: Israel's covenantal 'walking' (conduct) required constant divine support and therapeutic intervention. The 'did not know' (<em>velo yada</em>) is the same covenant-ignorance diagnosis as throughout the book — they were helped and didn't recognize the helper.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'I led them with cords of kindness, with the bands of love, and I became to them as one who eases the yoke on their jaws, and I bent down to them and fed them.' The 'cords of kindness' (<em>chavlei adam</em>) are contrasted with the 'cords of deceit' that bind Israel's enemies. The image of easing the yoke is from the practice of loosening the yoke on a working animal so it can eat — an act of care in the midst of labor. 'Bent down to them and fed them' (<em>va'et elehem ochil</em>) — the image of a parent bending to feed a small child. The divine condescension embedded in the covenant relationship: YHWH stoops to feed Israel even as they turn away.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'They shall not return to the land of Egypt, but Assyria shall be their king, because they have refused to return to me.' The 'shall not return to Egypt' may be a correction of the earlier prophecy (they shall return to Egypt, 8:13, 9:3) or a distinction: while some will flee to Egypt, the national fate is Assyrian captivity. 'Because they refused to return to me' (<em>ki me'anu lashuv</em>) — the refusal is the precise opposite of the <em>teshuvah</em> call; Israel refused the return to YHWH and will be returned to a foreign yoke instead. Assyria as king replaces YHWH as king — the covenant protector replaced by the conquering enemy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The sword shall rage against his cities, consume his gate bars, and devour them because of their own counsels.' The 'gate bars' (<em>badav</em>) are the wooden bars that secured city gates — the last line of defense. Their consumption by the sword means the cities are open. 'Their own counsels' (<em>me'atzoteihem</em>) — the self-generated plans of Israel's foreign policy (the Egyptian alliance, the assassinations, the tribute-paying) become the cause of their destruction. The Deuteronomic logic: the consequences of rebellion are inherent in the rebellion itself, not externally imposed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'My people are bent on turning away from me, and though they call out to the Most High, he shall not raise them up at all.' 'Bent on turning away' (<em>taluyim limeshuv'ati</em>) — the image is of being suspended between two directions, with the weight pulling toward apostasy. The call to 'the Most High' (<em>el</em>) while refusing to turn back is the precise definition of religious hypocrisy: calling on God while the heart faces the other direction. The 'Most High' (<em>al</em>) is a title emphasizing divine sovereignty — Israel appeals to divine power while refusing the divine covenant.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'How can I give you up, O Ephraim? How can I hand you over, O Israel? How can I make you like Admah? How can I treat you like Zeboiim? My heart recoils within me; my compassion grows warm and tender.' The divine soliloquy — YHWH wrestling with his own judgment. Admah and Zeboiim are cities of the plain destroyed with Sodom and Gomorrah (Deut 29:23) — their destruction was total and unreversed. The fourfold 'how can I?' (<em>eich</em>) is the language of anguish, not resignation. 'My heart recoils within me' (<em>nehpach aleiy libbi</em>) — literally my heart turns over within me; 'my compassion grows warm' (<em>nkhmru nichum'ay</em>) — the bowels of mercy heated. This is among the most anthropopathic passages in the prophets — divine love wrestling with divine justice.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'I will not execute my burning anger; I will not again destroy Ephraim; for I am God and not a man, the Holy One in your midst, and I will not come in wrath.' The theological resolution: 'I am God and not a man' (<em>ki El anochi velo ish</em>) — the distinction between divine and human anger. Human anger is subject to pride, wounded honor, and uncontrolled passion; divine anger is purposive and can be superseded by divine love. 'The Holy One in your midst' (<em>Qadosh begerevcha</em>) — YHWH's holiness is not mere transcendence but intimate presence. The restraint of wrath here anticipates the NT claim that God's love in Christ supersedes retributive judgment (Rom 5:8-9).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'They shall walk after the LORD; he will roar like a lion; when he roars, his children shall come trembling from the west.' The lion's roar as the signal for Israel's return — the reversal of the lion imagery used for judgment (5:14, 13:7-8). In the ANE, the lion was a symbol of royal power; YHWH roaring as a lion to summon his people transforms the judgment symbol into a restoration signal. 'Trembling from the west' — the western exiles (perhaps those scattered in the Mediterranean world, or in the western parts of the Assyrian empire) will respond to the divine summons. The trembling is awe, not terror.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'They shall come trembling like birds from Egypt, and like doves from the land of Assyria, and I will return them to their homes, declares the LORD.' The dove image returns: in 7:11, the dove was 'silly, without sense,' fluttering between Egypt and Assyria. Here the same dove comes trembling from Egypt and Assyria as returning exile. The reversal is complete: the sources of captivity become the places of release. 'I will return them to their homes' (<em>hoshavtim al-bateihem</em>) — the divine resettlement; the covenant land restored to the exiles. This eschatological restoration is the horizon toward which the judgment-oracles are aimed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Ephraim has surrounded me with lies, and the house of Israel with deceit, but Judah still walks with God and is faithful to the Holy One.' The contrast between Ephraim (lies and deceit) and Judah (still walking with God) is significant context: Hosea's prophecy addressed the Northern Kingdom primarily, and Judah's relative faithfulness at this period (under Uzziah and then Jotham) was a contrast. However, Judah's faithfulness would not long outlast Hosea's ministry — Isaiah and Micah, Hosea's southern contemporaries, were already warning of Judah's coming judgment.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>'Ephraim feeds on the wind and pursues the east wind all day long; they multiply falsehood and violence; they make a treaty with Assyria, and oil is carried to Egypt.' The 'east wind' (<em>qadiym</em>) is the sirocco — the hot, dry, desert wind that destroys crops and is uniformly associated with disaster in the OT (cf. Ezek 19:12, Jon 4:8). Feeding on wind is doubly futile: neither the east wind nor the foreign alliances provide sustenance. The historical situation: Hoshea, Israel's last king, was playing both sides — paying tribute to Assyria (2 Kings 17:3) while secretly sending messengers to So of Egypt (2 Kings 17:4). 'Oil' carried to Egypt was likely an export payment for the promised military alliance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'The LORD has an indictment against Judah and will punish Jacob according to his ways; he will repay him according to his deeds.' The covenant lawsuit (<em>riv</em>) is the legal framework for prophecy: YHWH as prosecuting attorney, Israel/Jacob as defendant, the covenant as the law code. The shift to 'Jacob' (rather than Ephraim or Israel) is deliberate: vv3-6 will use the Jacob narrative as a mirror for the people. 'Jacob' names both the patriarch and the nation; the ancestor's story becomes the nation's story.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'In the womb he took his brother by the heel, and in his manhood he strove with God.' The Jacob narrative from Genesis is invoked as a typological mirror. The heel-grasping birth (Gen 25:26) — Jacob (<em>Ya'aqov</em>) means 'heel-grabber/supplanter' — represents aggressive, cunning self-advancement. 'In his manhood he strove with God' refers to the Peniel wrestling (Gen 32:24-32), where Jacob wrestled the divine figure through the night and would not let go until he received the blessing. The contrast with Israel's current behavior is implicit: Jacob at least wrestled with God and sought his blessing — Israel has stopped engaging God entirely.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'He strove with the angel and prevailed; he wept and sought his favor. He met God at Bethel, and there God spoke with him.' The Peniel wrestling (Gen 32:24-32) is fused with the Bethel encounter (Gen 28:10-22 and Gen 35:9-15). Jacob 'wept and sought his favor' (<em>yivk vayitchan-lo</em>) — weeping in prayer, earnest supplication. This is the model being offered to Israel: genuine wrestling with God, seeking his face, not abandoning the relationship in crisis. The Bethel encounter — where God spoke to Jacob — is held up as a positive model, in contrast to Hosea's consistent condemnation of what Bethel has become (4:15, 5:8, 10:5).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The LORD, the God of hosts, the LORD is his memorial name.' The full divine name — YHWH <em>Elohei Tzevaot</em>, YHWH of hosts — is the object of Jacob's wrestling, the name he sought at Peniel (Gen 32:29: 'Why do you ask my name?'). The 'memorial name' (<em>zikro</em>) refers to the name by which YHWH is to be remembered across generations (cf. Exod 3:15). Invoking the full covenant name here establishes the identity of the God with whom Jacob wrestled and the God with whom Israel is in covenant — the same YHWH whose memorial name demands ongoing acknowledgment.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'So you, by the help of your God, return, hold fast to love and justice, and wait continually for your God.' The pastoral application of the Jacob typology: what Jacob did at Peniel (returned, wrestled, held on) is what Israel must do — return (<em>tashuv</em>) to YHWH, hold fast to <em>chesed</em> (covenant love) and <em>mishpat</em> (justice), and wait (<em>qaveh</em>) for God. The three imperatives capture the essence of covenant faithfulness: relational return, ethical practice, and patient hope. This is Hosea's positive program in its most concise form.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'A merchant, in whose hands are false balances, he loves to oppress.' 'Canaan' (<em>Kena'an</em>) in the original text is both the name for Canaan/Phoenicia (the land of merchants) and the Hebrew word for 'merchant/trader' — a deliberate double meaning. Israel has become Canaanite — not just in its worship but in its commercial ethics. 'False balances' (<em>moznei mirmah</em>) are prohibited explicitly in Lev 19:35-36, Deut 25:13-16, Amos 8:5, Mic 6:11, and Prov 11:1. The merchant who loves (<em>ahav</em>) to oppress has turned covenant love toward commercial exploitation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Ephraim has said, Ah, but I am rich; I have found wealth for myself; in all my labors, they cannot find in me iniquity or sin.' The self-justification of prosperity theology: wealth as divine approval, commercial success as moral vindication. The phrase 'I have found wealth for myself' (<em>matsati ohn li</em>) — ON means both 'wealth' and 'strength/vigor' — echoes the language of Deuteronomy 8:17: 'you may say in your heart, My power and the might of my hand have gotten me this wealth.' The Deuteronomic warning against prosperity-amnesia is exactly what Ephraim is doing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'I am the LORD your God from the land of Egypt; I will again make you dwell in tents, as in the days of the appointed feast.' The self-identification formula ('I am the LORD your God from the land of Egypt') echoes the covenant prologue of Exod 20:2 and Deut 5:6 — the basis for the Ten Commandments. Making Israel 'dwell in tents' again is the wilderness-return theme: before the settlement and the prosperity that led to apostasy, Israel lived in tents before YHWH. The 'days of the appointed feast' (<em>yemei mo'ed</em>) specifically the Feast of Tabernacles, when Israel dwelt in booths to remember the wilderness — a yearly liturgical re-enactment that the people now must live literally.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'I spoke to the prophets; it was I who multiplied visions, and through the prophets I gave parables.' The self-description of the prophetic mode: YHWH spoke through <em>chazot</em> (visions) and <em>damiyti</em> (similitudes/parables). The multiplied prophets and visions were YHWH's persistent attempt to communicate with Israel before judgment — 'I have sent to you all my servants the prophets, sending them persistently' (Jer 7:25). Hosea himself is one of these multiplied prophets; the use of marriage-metaphor, agricultural imagery, and family narrative in his own book illustrates the 'parables' by which YHWH spoke.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'If there is iniquity in Gilead — surely they shall come to nothing! In Gilgal they sacrifice bulls; their altars also are like stone heaps on the furrows of the field.' Gilead (the Transjordanian territory) and Gilgal (the Jordan valley sanctuary, first campsite after the crossing) are both condemned as centers of false worship. The 'stone heaps on furrows' (<em>galim al-talme sadai</em>) is a precise agricultural image: fieldstones cleared from plowed ground and piled at the edges — the altars are as numerous and as worthless as these field-clearing heaps. The false altars have proliferated like the debris of agricultural labor.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Jacob fled to the land of Aram; there Israel served for a wife, and for a wife he kept sheep.' The third Jacob narrative reference: the flight to Haran (Gen 28:10, 29:1-30), the 14 years of service for Leah and Rachel. The mention of Jacob 'serving' (<em>abad</em>) for a wife is pointed: the patriarch who strove with God and wrestled a blessing submitted to human labor for love. Israel who will not serve YHWH is contrasted with Jacob who willingly served Laban. The shepherd-service of Jacob prefigures the prophet-service that will preserve Israel (v13).</p>",
    "13": "<p>'By a prophet the LORD brought Israel up from Egypt, and by a prophet he was kept.' Moses as the prophet who brought Israel out of Egypt (Exod 3-14) and 'kept' (<em>nishmar</em>) Israel in the wilderness — the verb suggests careful preservation, like a shepherd guarding a flock. The Jacob-who-served-for-a-wife (v12) contrast with Moses-who-served-for-Israel sets up a typology: the covenant mediator who gave himself for the people preserved by divine care. The prophet's role in Israel's history is foundational — Moses at the Exodus, the prophets in the monarchy. Hosea himself stands in this line.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Ephraim has given bitter provocation; so his Lord will leave his bloodguilt on him and will repay him for his disgraceful deeds.' The 'bitter provocation' (<em>hikis Ephraim tamrurim</em>) is the culmination of the Jacob typology: Jacob strove with God and prevailed; Ephraim provokes God and faces judgment. 'Bloodguilt' (<em>damav</em>) — the unpurged guilt of bloodshed (cf. the blood of Jezreel, 1:4) left on Ephraim without expiation. The 'disgraceful deeds' (<em>cherpato</em>, reproaches) that YHWH will return: the covenant mechanism of measure-for-measure judgment, the wages of rebellion paid back in kind.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'hosea')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'hosea', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'hosea mkt-context: added up to {total} verses across ch7-12')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
